@flexiarg vsatlatarium/arc-as-typed-relation
@title Arc as Typed Relation
@audience narrative system designers, knowledge graph practitioners
@tone analytic
@style design-pattern
@sigils [🌈/弧]
@references [vsatlas/non-destructive-relational-layers vsatlas/three-layer-architecture]

! conclusion:
  Render inter-story links as coloured, curved arcs with type, status, and
  rationale so relational meaning is visible geometry, not hidden metadata.

  + context: You are making the interpretive layer legible as spatial form. This does not apply when link volume is so high that arcs would become visual noise.
  + IF:
    Viewers need to see why stories are connected — not just that they are.

  + HOWEVER:
    Undifferentiated lines flatten thematic, causal, adjacency, and contrast
    links into a single "related" signal.

  + THEN:
    Colour arcs by link type, modulate opacity by status (accepted bright,
    proposed mid, retired faint), and bow arcs inward (planetarium) or
    outward (geomview) so they read as spatial bridges rather than flat
    edges. Provide legend toggles to show/hide types independently.

  + BECAUSE:
    Typed arcs externalise the interpretive grammar that VSATLAS
    contributors use when proposing connections, making review and
    discussion concrete rather than abstract.

  + STATUS:
    status[ready]
    evidence[VSATLATARIUM arc rendering — colour by type, opacity by status, legend toggles]

  + NEXT-STEPS:
    next[Add arc hover interaction showing link rationale text in-scene.]
    next[Measure whether typed arcs improve participants' ability to articulate connection reasons.]
    next[Define a visual-noise threshold (arc count) where filtering or aggregation becomes necessary.]
